<h3>
    AP Physics Summer Work
</h3>

<h4>
    Guidelines
</h4>

<ul>
    <li>
        The summer work is not all due on the first day, but is spread throughout the first month of the year.
    </li>
    <li>
        After the year begins, <strong>more work</strong> will be assigned.
        The summer work is a selection of assignments that can give you a head start
        so you are not overwhelmed once the year begins.
    </li>
    <li>
        If one or two of the assignments are difficult, you can ask questions of me,
        or wait until the school year begins.
    </li>
    <li>
        During the first quarter, we will learn the basics of each topic in the curriculum,
        so that in quarters two and three we can go in depth into more challenging problems.
        Thus, the summer work includes a assignments from many different areas of physics.
    </li>
    <li>
        Please <strong>hand write</strong> all assignments.
        You can chose to either print the assignments and hand write them,
        or complete them on a separate page.
        This guideline is in place because I want students to go slowly and think through each problem.
        (Which they often don't when typing.)
    </li>
    <li>
        If we begin the year with remote learning, you will turn in your assignments as photos of handwritten pages.
    </li>
    <li>
        For math-based for formula-based assignments, please show the steps necessary to solve each problem.
        You will not receive credit for merely copying the answers.
    </li>
    <li>
        The answers are included in most of the assignments.
        I do want you to check your work.
        Early in the year, there will be <strong>quizzes</strong> on all these topics.
        If you just copy the answers and don't do the work, you will not be able to hide it.
    </li>
</ul>

